<major-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.0.mh" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm">Written Answers Tuesday 6 March 2007</major-heading>

<major-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.1.mh" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm">Scottish Executive</major-heading>

<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.2.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">Carers</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.2.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80059" speakername="Carolyn Leckie (Central Scotland) (SSP)" spid="S2W-31900" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive whether, in light of the findings published in the Care 21 report, <em>The Future of Unpaid Care in Scotland</em> , it will ensure that all local authorities (a) inform all eligible carers of their right to a carers&rsquo; assessment, (b) ensure that all carers receive an individual assessment within a reasonable timescale and (c) improve the quality of carers&rsquo; assessments to ensure that all carers receive the support and resources they need and that the assessment makes an appreciable difference to their lives.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.2.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80064" speakername="Lewis Macdonald" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">

  <p>Both the Executive and local partnerships have taken a number of steps to improve the take-up of carer assessments.</p>

  <p>The Community Care and Health (Scotland) Act 2002 gives carers the right to an assessment of their ability to care. The legislation requires local authorities to inform them of this right.</p>

  <p>We have required local partnerships to report on local improvement targets to increase numbers of carer assessments.</p>

  <p>NHS Carer Information Strategies, which will take effect from April, will help to improve carer identification and support. Crucially, they will include systems to inform carers of their right to assessment.</p>

  <p>It is for individual local authorities to allocate resources, in light of local needs and priorities, to ensure adequate service delivery.</p>

</reply>


<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.3.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">Carers</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.3.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80059" speakername="Carolyn Leckie (Central Scotland) (SSP)" spid="S2W-31901" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive what information it has on the number of public bodies that have implemented employment policies for carers.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.3.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80064" speakername="Lewis Macdonald" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">

  <p>This information is not held centrally.</p>

</reply>


<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.4.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">Carers</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.4.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80059" speakername="Carolyn Leckie (Central Scotland) (SSP)" spid="S2W-31902" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive what representations it has made to the UK Government to ensure that every public and private employer implements employment policies for carers.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.4.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80064" speakername="Lewis Macdonald" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#1">

  <p>Following the publication of the Care 21 report: <em>The Future of Unpaid Care in Scotland</em> in April 2006, I wrote to UK ministers to draw to their attention the report&rsquo;s recommendations on the reserved issue of employment rights.</p>

</reply>


<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.5.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#2">Ferry Services</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.5.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80072" speakername="Jim Mather (Highlands and Islands) (SNP)" spid="S2W-31530" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#2" holdingdate="2007-02-13">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive what total costs have been incurred by (a) it, (b) other public bodies and (c) Caledonian MacBrayne and its successor companies in relation to the tender for the Clyde and Hebrides ferry services since 1999, including (i) civil servants&rsquo; time and related costs, including the time of senior civil servants, (ii) the costs of dividing Caledonian MacBrayne into three companies, offshoring jobs and transferring ownership, including establishing new offices at Port Glasgow and in Jersey, (iii) the costs of all external legal advice sought by the Executive, (iv) the costs to any Executive agency or organisation funded by the Executive in relation to the tender and (v) any other associated costs.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2007-03-06.5.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80109" speakername="Tavish Scott" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-07/wa0306.htm#2">

